Mini Project: Live Character Counter
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

function CharacterCounter() {

    const [text, setText] = useState("");

    useEffect(() => {
        document.title = `Characters: ${text.length}`;
    }, [text]);

    return (
        <div>
            <h2>Character Counter</h2>

            <input
                type="text"
                value={text}
                onChange={(e) => setText(e.target.value)}
            />

            <p>Characters: {text.length}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default CharacterCounter;


React Component Lifecycle (Simplified)
1. Mounting

Component is created and displayed.

App starts
↓
Welcome component created
↓
Welcome component shown on screen

useEffect(..., []) runs here.

useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Mounted");
}, []);

Output:

Mounted
2. Updating

When state or props change.

const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

Click button:

setCount(count + 1);

Component updates and re-renders.

Count: 0
↓
Count: 1
↓
Count: 2
3. Unmounting

Component is removed from the screen.

Example:

{
    show && <Welcome />
}

When:

setShow(false);

React removes <Welcome /> from the page.

Component Unmounted
Visual Example
function App() {

    const [show, setShow] = useState(true);

    return (
        <div>
            <button onClick={() => setShow(!show)}>
                Toggle
            </button>

            {show && <Welcome />}
        </div>
    );
}

When page loads:

Welcome Mounted

Click Toggle:

Welcome Unmounted

Click Toggle again:

Welcome Mounted
Why is React StrictMode showing it twice?

In development:

Mount
↓
Unmount
↓
Mount Again

React does this intentionally to help detect bugs in useEffect.

That's why you saw:

Component loaded
Component loaded

even though your effect has:

useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Component loaded");
}, []);

A useful way to remember it:

Mount = Component appears on screen for the first time.
Update = Component re-renders because state/props changed.
Unmount = Component is removed from the screen.



